= Environmental Responses
- Life histories respond to environmental variation.
- Resource storage and dormancy are strategies to cope with scarcity.
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.14").path, width: 50%)
)
- Dormancy: physiological inactivity during unfavorable conditions (e.g., hibernation, diapause).

= Timing and Cues
- Life history changes are triggered by proximate (e.g., photoperiod) and ultimate (e.g., food supply) factors.
- Sensitivity to cues is shaped by natural selection.

= Individual Variation and Reaction Norms
- Individuals adjust life history traits in response to environmental variation.
- Reaction norm: relationship between age and size at maturation under different conditions.
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.15").path, width: 50%)
)
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.16").path, width: 50%)
)
- Predation risk and resource availability influence growth and development.
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.17").path, width: 50%)
)

= Behavioral Adaptations: Foraging
- Animals optimize foraging to maximize fitness, balancing time, reward, and risk.
- Central place foraging: parents balance travel and search time to maximize food delivery.
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.18").path, width: 50%)
)
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.19").path, width: 50%)
)
- Risk-sensitive foraging: animals avoid high-risk areas unless food rewards are high.
#figure(
  image(images.at("7.20").path, width: 50%)
)

= Summary
- Life history traits are shaped by trade-offs and environmental variation.
- Evolutionary theory explains diversity in life histories.
- Individual and population-level responses optimize fitness under changing conditions.
